<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,721,1466]" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,721,746]" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Female.</emphasis>
Identical to male but slightly larger and without a dark forewing costa. Antennae similar to male but just ciliate. Abdomen with a slightly yellowish tinge dorsally. Forewing length 
<quantity box="[1044,1166,758,782]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="231" unit="mm" value="12.5" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="12.0">12‒13 mm</quantity>
(n = 9). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1264,1374,757,782]" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 51‒54" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1295,1317]" captionTargetBox="[155,1423,720,1264]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,700,1273]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 51‒54. Gloora alba comb. nov. (51), G. mundula comb. nov. (52), G. sericea comb. nov. (53), G. canae sp. nov. (54), female genitalia (bursae). Scale bars: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452151/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
). Genitalia generally slightly sclerotized, apophyses anteriores and posteriores subequal, thin and long. Ductus bursae as a narrow cylindrical tube strongly bent and sinuous in the last third where it is strongly sclerotized. Bursa copulatrix, first almost cylindrical and smooth then large and almost spherical, strongly sclerotized at the narrow end near the junction with ductus bursae. Bursa covered with spicules on its entire surface except near the junction with the ductus bursae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,721,1466]" box="[199,490,973,998]" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">
