<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="231" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,721,1466]" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1153,1178]" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Biology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Boppré" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Druce" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[308,452,1153,1177]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Gloora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis box="[308,452,1153,1177]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Gloora alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibits pharmacophagy with respect to pyrrolizidine alkaloids (PAs); it has been reported to be attracted to 
<taxonomicName box="[459,708,1189,1213]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Heliotropium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="5" pageNumber="231" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="species" species="indicum">
<emphasis box="[459,708,1189,1213]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Heliotropium indicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a source of PAs, in 
<collectingCountry box="[955,1070,1189,1214]" name="Venezuela" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
at 
<quantity box="[1110,1204,1190,1214]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="231" unit="m" value="1.1">1,100 m</quantity>
by 
<bibRefCitation pageId="5" pageNumber="231" refId="ref7730" refString="Pliske, T. E. (1975) Attraction of Lepidoptera to plants containing pyrrolizidine alkaloids. Environmental Entomology, 4, 455 - 473. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / ee / 4.3.455" type="journal article">
Pliske (1975; as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Druce" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[151,315,1225,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Eucereon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis box="[151,315,1225,1249]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Eucereon alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)
</bibRefCitation>
; strong attraction of both sexes to various pure PAs and PA-containing plants in evenings has also been found in 
<collectingCountry box="[310,432,1261,1286]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
by P. Gloor (MB unpubl., cf. 
<figureCitation box="[764,832,1261,1286]" captionStart="FIGURES 1‒4" captionStartId="1.[151,264,491,513]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,474]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,190,474]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1‒4. Gloora alba comb. nov., habitus female (1, 2) and male (3) and both sexes gathering pyrrolizidine alkaloids from dry roots of Emilia sp. (Asteraceae) (4)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452135/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Both sexes are attracted to artificial light, too. Males possess interesting tymbal (see 
<figureCitation box="[515,651,1297,1322]" captionStart="FIGURES 55‒57" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1842,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,1417,1802]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,1417,1807]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 55‒57. Gloora alba comb. nov., scanning electron micrographs of a female tymbal organ after brushing off the overlying scales (55, 56) and a spectrogram (57) showing a modulation cycle with ten clicks in the active and passive modulation half cycle. The acoustic structure of sounds produced in response to manual stimulation meets the general assumptions on arctiine sound production (Blest et al. 1963; Fullard &amp; Fenton 1977) but differ insofar as the passive modulation half cycles are in comparison to the respective active cycles less emphasized, i.e. with lower overall amplitude of the click trains. Courtesy of Philipp Klein, FZE, Freiburg (cf. Klein et al. 2018). Scale bars: 100 µm / 5 msec." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452153/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">Figs. 55‒57</figureCitation>
) and androconial organs and emit pheromones which are detectable with the human nose―details will be reported elsewhere (Boppré 
<emphasis box="[893,949,1333,1357]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="231">et al.</emphasis>
in prep.).
</paragraph>
